1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:01,360
Why are you still dating U?

2
00:00:01,520 --> 00:00:02,480
If he was using me,
he might have run away already.

3
00:00:03,440 --> 00:00:06,160
So if he chooses to stay,
that must mean that he loves me.

4
00:00:06,160 --> 00:00:07,400
As long as you’re still married to Tim,

5
00:00:07,520 --> 00:00:11,040
this land is a marital asset
and belongs to both you and Tim.

6
00:00:11,240 --> 00:00:13,640
I suggest you get a proper divorce
before managing this property.

7
00:00:14,000 --> 00:00:15,200
You went to dinner
with Mr. Pai last night, right?

8
00:00:15,560 --> 00:00:16,480
Didn’t you guys make up?

9
00:00:16,480 --> 00:00:17,840
Pai said he wants a divorce.

10
00:00:18,280 --> 00:00:19,360
I already agreed to it.

11
00:00:22,720 --> 00:00:23,720
This is not a ruse, is it?

12
00:00:24,800 --> 00:00:26,160
You’re always like this, baby.

13
00:00:26,400 --> 00:00:27,200
I don’t like it.

14
00:00:27,200 --> 00:00:28,360
What did you just call me?

15
00:00:29,800 --> 00:00:32,280
From the look of it, I don’t think
they’re getting divorced.

16
00:00:46,000 --> 00:00:47,480
I don’t think we have time
to do anything else today.

17
00:00:47,600 --> 00:00:48,600
We’ll get a divorce some other day.

18
00:00:50,280 --> 00:00:50,840
Yes!

19
00:00:51,640 --> 00:00:52,200
Hey.

20
00:00:53,080 --> 00:00:54,200
Are you sure this wasn’t a ruse?

21
00:00:55,960 --> 00:00:57,000
Of course, it wasn’t.

22
00:00:57,440 --> 00:00:58,840
I had to get stitches, you know?

23
00:01:00,760 --> 00:01:04,040
I think you should take Tim
home to get some rest.

24
00:01:04,320 --> 00:01:06,320
U and I will take care of things
at the bakery.

25
00:01:07,560 --> 00:01:08,560
Can you even drive?

26
00:01:09,320 --> 00:01:09,960
Of course.

27
00:01:11,120 --> 00:01:11,760
You sure?

28
00:01:13,440 --> 00:01:14,040
Yeah.

29
00:01:14,880 --> 00:01:16,400
As if I can afford to be reckless
when Pai is with me.

30
00:01:17,920 --> 00:01:20,040
Oh, wow, Mr. Sweet Talker.

31
00:01:22,520 --> 00:01:24,880
You’re even more of a sweet talker
as an ex than as a boyfriend.

32
00:01:26,120 --> 00:01:27,200
I’m not buttering him up.

33
00:01:27,600 --> 00:01:28,240
I’m serious.

34
00:01:29,560 --> 00:01:30,120
Alright.
Drive safe.

35
00:01:30,680 --> 00:01:32,640
North and I will head to work.

36
00:01:37,280 --> 00:01:37,800
Let’s get going.

37
00:01:38,400 --> 00:01:39,480
You gotta hold on to me.

38
00:01:39,480 --> 00:01:40,080
I’m still in pain.

39
00:01:41,920 --> 00:01:42,760
I feel faint.

40
00:01:43,960 --> 00:01:44,760
Quit the theatrics.

41
00:01:45,560 --> 00:01:46,320
I just felt faint.

42
00:01:46,840 --> 00:01:47,320
Quit it.

43
00:01:48,120 --> 00:01:49,800
Hold on to me, alright?

44
00:03:04,240 --> 00:03:05,840
U, you were going so fast.

45
00:03:06,360 --> 00:03:07,320
Can’t help that
I have an amazing motorbike.

46
00:03:09,600 --> 00:03:10,760
I bet that’s all that’s amazing.

47
00:03:11,800 --> 00:03:12,520
I’m even more amazing.

48
00:03:19,560 --> 00:03:20,120
Let’s go.

49
00:03:23,000 --> 00:03:24,120
Oh, hey.

50
00:03:24,280 --> 00:03:25,000
Perfect timing.

51
00:03:25,560 --> 00:03:27,720
Vanness just texted me
about our end-of-the-year trip.

52
00:03:29,560 --> 00:03:30,240
What trip?

53
00:03:31,280 --> 00:03:32,960
The South African safari trip.

54
00:03:33,440 --> 00:03:34,800
You free at the beginning of December?

55
00:03:35,280 --> 00:03:36,000
Hold on.

56
00:03:36,200 --> 00:03:37,360
If I’m not here, we can’t open the bakery.

57
00:03:37,360 --> 00:03:38,080
Which means you’re free.

58
00:03:38,080 --> 00:03:39,200
Alright. I’ll just confirm him.

59
00:03:39,200 --> 00:03:39,920
Hold on.

60
00:03:41,720 --> 00:03:42,920
I don’t think I can go.

61
00:03:44,720 --> 00:03:45,240
Why not?

62
00:03:46,280 --> 00:03:47,000
Well…

63
00:03:47,880 --> 00:03:48,920
I don’t have money.

64
00:03:49,320 --> 00:03:50,920
And I don’t think I can make enough
before December.

65
00:03:50,920 --> 00:03:52,200
I’ll lend you some.

66
00:03:54,400 --> 00:03:55,200
How about this?

67
00:03:55,520 --> 00:03:56,360
My treat.

68
00:03:57,120 --> 00:03:58,000
Take U with us.
We can all go.

69
00:03:59,560 --> 00:04:00,200
That solves everything, right?
My treat.

70
00:04:00,920 --> 00:04:01,840
Wait, wait, wait.

71
00:04:02,520 --> 00:04:03,640
I don’t want you to.

72
00:04:03,960 --> 00:04:05,840
I know now how hard
making money really is.

73
00:04:06,000 --> 00:04:06,760
You guys go.

74
00:04:07,040 --> 00:04:08,800
Just make sure you say hello
to Simba for me.

75
00:04:11,680 --> 00:04:13,240
Fine, then.

76
00:04:14,680 --> 00:04:15,680
That’s too bad.

77
00:04:17,640 --> 00:04:19,240
How is Tim, though?

78
00:04:20,000 --> 00:04:21,200
He went home to rest.

79
00:04:24,040 --> 00:04:26,400
I WANT TO WIN

80
00:04:31,120 --> 00:04:33,840
I WANT TO WIN THE LOTTERY!

81
00:04:34,920 --> 00:04:35,880
What’s wrong?

82
00:04:37,120 --> 00:04:39,000
You actually want to go to South Africa,
don’t you?

83
00:04:40,280 --> 00:04:41,920
Of course, I do.

84
00:04:42,440 --> 00:04:45,400
But when I think I have to
spend my friend’s money,

85
00:04:47,000 --> 00:04:47,960
it just feels kinda weird.

86
00:04:50,760 --> 00:04:54,920
Then I bet you’ll like your
grandfather’s offer, Mr. North.

87
00:04:56,960 --> 00:04:57,720
Ms. Nana.

88
00:05:00,840 --> 00:05:01,760
What offer?

89
00:05:02,800 --> 00:05:05,800
Your grandfather wants you to go back
and learn the trade at Empire.

90
00:05:06,240 --> 00:05:06,920
What?

91
00:05:09,080 --> 00:05:10,600
What exactly are you doing, Grandpa?

92
00:05:10,600 --> 00:05:14,520
I’ve been watching you and Pai.

93
00:05:15,000 --> 00:05:16,400
And I have seen that

94
00:05:16,400 --> 00:05:19,680
I can get by on my own, can work a proper job, with U still by my si..

95
00:05:19,680 --> 00:05:22,320
I have seen that you cannot
get by on your own.

96
00:05:23,240 --> 00:05:24,000
I can!
I so can!

97
00:05:25,720 --> 00:05:26,520
Is that right?

98
00:05:27,080 --> 00:05:30,080
If you were to work
somewhere else right now,

99
00:05:30,880 --> 00:05:32,600
what skills do you think you have to offer?

100
00:05:33,320 --> 00:05:35,560
And I’m not talking about waiting tables
and cleaning windows.

101
00:05:38,600 --> 00:05:42,840
What happens next when
Pure gets sick of this bakery?

102
00:05:44,600 --> 00:05:47,280
With Pai there, I guess
you can keep it up and running.

103
00:05:47,280 --> 00:05:49,880
But if Pai finds something to do
on his own,

104
00:05:50,840 --> 00:05:53,000
how will you support yourself, North?

105
00:05:55,640 --> 00:05:57,120
Come back and work for me.

106
00:05:58,040 --> 00:06:03,640
Prove to me that you’re mature enough
to take care of yourself.

107
00:06:05,400 --> 00:06:08,760
If you prove yourself a capable employee,
I’ll forgive you.

108
00:06:15,320 --> 00:06:16,560
If you want me to work for you,

109
00:06:17,120 --> 00:06:18,600
U is coming with me.

110
00:06:19,400 --> 00:06:21,520
Otherwise, it’s a no right here and now.

111
00:06:25,200 --> 00:06:25,800
Sure.

112
00:06:32,320 --> 00:06:33,720
What’s wrong, U?

113
00:06:39,200 --> 00:06:39,800
North.

114
00:06:40,280 --> 00:06:41,840
What do you think of
your Grandpa’s offer?

115
00:06:43,680 --> 00:06:45,040
If you pass this training,

116
00:06:45,040 --> 00:06:48,440
you have to work for Empire
for at least 10 years.

117
00:06:50,600 --> 00:06:54,920
If I said yes, you’d be stuck
with Empire for 10 years.

118
00:06:57,040 --> 00:06:57,760
But…

119
00:06:58,520 --> 00:07:01,080
I think it’s best for you to take the offer.

120
00:07:07,120 --> 00:07:10,920
I don’t think it’s going to be
as easy as you think.

121
00:07:11,880 --> 00:07:14,680
I bet it’s just a ruse that
he wants us to be salespersons.

122
00:07:14,800 --> 00:07:18,960
At Empire, everything we do
will be scrutinized.

123
00:07:19,440 --> 00:07:20,360
It would be so uncomfortable!

124
00:07:24,760 --> 00:07:28,680
North, you know what makes me
feel uncomfortable?

125
00:07:32,480 --> 00:07:38,680
What makes me feel uncomfortable
is the fact that I can’t support you.

126
00:07:40,160 --> 00:07:43,880
I can’t take care of you the way
you deserve to be taken care of.

127
00:07:44,280 --> 00:07:48,160
So I will do anything.

128
00:07:48,920 --> 00:07:50,440
If I have to force you,

129
00:07:50,920 --> 00:07:55,000
or swoop your bum like a child to get
you to reconcile with your Grandpa,

130
00:07:55,840 --> 00:07:56,760
I’ll do it.

131
00:07:58,960 --> 00:07:59,640
Fine.

132
00:08:00,760 --> 00:08:02,080
I’ll take his offer.

133
00:08:02,760 --> 00:08:05,280
I just want to play hard to get for,

134
00:08:05,800 --> 00:08:08,280
like, four… or five hours.

135
00:08:08,560 --> 00:08:09,120
Oh?

136
00:08:10,840 --> 00:08:11,680
Sure thing.

137
00:08:13,960 --> 00:08:14,560
Let’s go.

138
00:08:17,840 --> 00:08:18,360
Here.

139
00:08:20,960 --> 00:08:21,800
Thank you.

140
00:08:25,480 --> 00:08:26,560
Hold on tight.

141
00:08:26,560 --> 00:08:27,320
I know that.

142
00:08:38,600 --> 00:08:39,560
Can I come in?

143
00:08:40,040 --> 00:08:40,600
Umm.

144
00:08:46,320 --> 00:08:47,760
You know how to knock now.

145
00:08:48,280 --> 00:08:50,120
Only because I thought Tim could be here.

146
00:08:50,400 --> 00:08:51,560
I didn’t want to interrupt.

147
00:08:54,680 --> 00:08:56,080
How were things at the bakery today?

148
00:09:01,120 --> 00:09:02,320
Actually…

149
00:09:03,320 --> 00:09:04,640
I wasn’t there.

150
00:09:04,840 --> 00:09:05,400
What?

151
00:09:06,200 --> 00:09:07,200
Then where have you been?

152
00:09:07,320 --> 00:09:09,760
Grandpa sent Ms. Nana to fetch me.

153
00:09:11,720 --> 00:09:16,440
So Grandpa wants me and U
to intern at the mall.

154
00:09:16,440 --> 00:09:18,480
If we pass the training,
we’ll go on to intern at the office.

155
00:09:18,960 --> 00:09:21,480
He also wants us to work there
for 10 years!

156
00:09:21,920 --> 00:09:23,200
That’s when he’ll forgive me.

157
00:09:29,880 --> 00:09:30,760
That was all?

158
00:09:35,760 --> 00:09:38,640
I asked him about you as well.

159
00:09:40,600 --> 00:09:42,080
Grandpa said…

160
00:09:42,560 --> 00:09:43,800
“If he thinks he’s so smart,

161
00:09:44,480 --> 00:09:49,320
he can think for himself what he should do
for me to forgive him.”

162
00:09:50,840 --> 00:09:51,560
That’s it.

163
00:09:56,520 --> 00:09:58,760
If he had planned to forgive me at all,

164
00:09:59,720 --> 00:10:01,520
he would have made me an offer
like he did with you.

165
00:10:02,040 --> 00:10:02,840
But that’s not the case.

166
00:10:04,360 --> 00:10:05,720
So whatever I do, it’ll be futile.

167
00:10:08,520 --> 00:10:09,960
Turn the light off when you leave.

168
00:10:10,280 --> 00:10:11,480
I’m gonna turn in for the night.

169
00:10:12,240 --> 00:10:14,080
It’s 7 p.m.?

170
00:10:14,240 --> 00:10:15,080
I’m tired.

171
00:10:29,560 --> 00:10:31,040
Where did you get those uniforms?

172
00:10:32,400 --> 00:10:34,200
Ms. Nana sent them.

173
00:10:34,760 --> 00:10:35,400
Right.

174
00:10:38,000 --> 00:10:38,960
Pai is still asleep?

175
00:10:39,760 --> 00:10:41,440
Was he up late crunching numbers?

176
00:10:42,520 --> 00:10:43,040
No.

177
00:10:43,040 --> 00:10:44,840
Pai went to bed at 7 p.m.

178
00:10:45,720 --> 00:10:46,920
I’ll check up on him.

179
00:10:48,400 --> 00:10:51,080
We’re getting a divorce before work today.

180
00:10:52,440 --> 00:10:54,480
Why did you pack?

181
00:10:55,040 --> 00:10:56,840
Are you moving house?

182
00:10:57,040 --> 00:10:57,920
Where are you going?

183
00:10:58,200 --> 00:10:59,040
That’s my business.

184
00:11:00,560 --> 00:11:01,520
Ugh.

185
00:11:02,320 --> 00:11:03,920
You don’t have to move.

186
00:11:04,160 --> 00:11:06,000
I’ll let you stay even if we’re divorced.

187
00:11:06,320 --> 00:11:10,600
When Grandpa softens up,
U and North will move back to the condo.

188
00:11:11,120 --> 00:11:13,600
It would be weird for you and me
to stay under the same roof all alone.

189
00:11:13,720 --> 00:11:14,680
It’s not!
It’s not!

190
00:11:17,200 --> 00:11:17,720
See?
This has nothing to do with me, though.

191
00:11:19,200 --> 00:11:20,200
Sure, it’s not.

192
00:11:21,320 --> 00:11:22,280
But I still don’t want to.
Oh.

193
00:11:24,480 --> 00:11:25,640
It’s time to stop playing around.

194
00:11:26,360 --> 00:11:28,680
I’m getting a divorce today!

195
00:11:39,240 --> 00:11:39,880
Sign it.

196
00:11:47,800 --> 00:11:50,000
Ugh. This pen’s out of ink.

197
00:11:50,000 --> 00:11:50,880
Divorce is off.

198
00:11:52,840 --> 00:11:54,120
It’s working just fine.

199
00:11:58,960 --> 00:12:00,200
It’s out of ink.

200
00:12:00,200 --> 00:12:01,280
It’s not.
It’s not.

201
00:12:02,360 --> 00:12:03,240
It is, sir.

202
00:12:03,560 --> 00:12:04,480
It’s not.
It’s not.

203
00:12:04,720 --> 00:12:06,640
I’m literally showing you I can’t write with it.

204
00:12:06,640 --> 00:12:08,480
I told you it’s out of ink.

205
00:12:12,960 --> 00:12:14,040
Take your pick.

206
00:12:20,520 --> 00:12:21,640
No ink, either.

207
00:12:24,160 --> 00:12:26,240
Uh, I can’t write with this one as well.

208
00:12:26,520 --> 00:12:29,080
You gotta work on your quality control.

209
00:12:43,040 --> 00:12:44,000
Behave yourself.

210
00:12:44,280 --> 00:12:45,600
Don’t look so ecstatic.

211
00:12:46,400 --> 00:12:48,720
I hope to never see you again.

212
00:12:49,560 --> 00:12:51,320
I’m still working at your bakery, though.

213
00:12:51,320 --> 00:12:52,320
You’re fired.

214
00:12:52,600 --> 00:12:53,160
What?

215
00:12:54,080 --> 00:12:55,000
You okay with that, North?

216
00:12:55,440 --> 00:12:56,080
What?
What?

217
00:12:56,840 --> 00:12:57,560
There you go.

218
00:12:59,160 --> 00:12:59,800
Thank you, sir.

219
00:13:02,400 --> 00:13:03,240
Pai.

220
00:13:11,880 --> 00:13:12,720
Where are you going?

221
00:13:12,960 --> 00:13:13,800
Do you need a ride?

222
00:13:14,520 --> 00:13:15,200
No, I don’t.

223
00:13:15,680 --> 00:13:16,640
I already have a ride.

224
00:13:17,800 --> 00:13:18,480
What?

225
00:13:19,280 --> 00:13:20,200
Don’t tell me it’s Kuea
My new date.

226
00:13:21,640 --> 00:13:22,400
What?

227
00:13:23,520 --> 00:13:26,400
Who is he? How did you know him?

228
00:13:26,520 --> 00:13:27,280
When did you meet him?
Can you even trust him?

229
00:13:28,320 --> 00:13:29,680
Is he a customer?

230
00:13:30,000 --> 00:13:30,560
No.

231
00:13:31,120 --> 00:13:32,600
I met him online last night.

232
00:13:32,880 --> 00:13:33,560
Alright?

233
00:13:38,000 --> 00:13:38,920
Are you Pai?

234
00:13:39,040 --> 00:13:39,560
Yes.

235
00:13:42,960 --> 00:13:45,440
Oh, dear. Oh, dear.

236
00:13:47,320 --> 00:13:48,720
What on earth…

237
00:13:50,080 --> 00:13:51,520
What the hell is he thinking?

238
00:13:55,160 --> 00:13:56,200
I don’t trust him.

239
00:13:56,480 --> 00:13:58,560
Y’all can tell that man’s a jerk, right?

240
00:13:58,560 --> 00:13:59,480
Sure thing.

241
00:14:00,080 --> 00:14:00,600
Right.

242
00:14:01,040 --> 00:14:02,480
What if something happens to Pai?

243
00:14:02,480 --> 00:14:03,520
We’d better follow him!

244
00:14:03,520 --> 00:14:04,320
Tim, no!
Hold on!
Take it easy!

245
00:14:04,720 --> 00:14:05,200
Tim.

246
00:14:05,600 --> 00:14:08,000
U and I have to go to work at Empire.

247
00:14:08,000 --> 00:14:09,520
It’ll be 10 p.m. when we’re off work.

248
00:14:09,560 --> 00:14:11,920
Are we supposed to just let Pai go?

249
00:14:12,240 --> 00:14:13,080
Tim.

250
00:14:13,360 --> 00:14:16,600
You know you can’t stop Pai
once he sets his mind on something.

251
00:14:21,360 --> 00:14:22,080
Alright.

252
00:14:22,920 --> 00:14:25,680
I’ll find out where he’s staying right now.

253
00:14:25,920 --> 00:14:26,680
How about that?

254
00:14:29,040 --> 00:14:29,800
Thanks, North.

255
00:14:44,120 --> 00:14:47,520
Uhh, what did you say
you do for a living again?

256
00:14:48,240 --> 00:14:51,000
I have a dehydrated fruit business.

257
00:14:51,400 --> 00:14:53,880
Our products are placed
at airports and such.

258
00:14:53,880 --> 00:14:55,280
What about you, Pai?

259
00:14:55,320 --> 00:14:56,120
What do you do for a living?

260
00:14:56,280 --> 00:14:57,520
I run a mall

261
00:14:57,880 --> 00:14:58,640
Wow.
Wait, no.

262
00:15:00,040 --> 00:15:01,880
I help run a bakery.

263
00:15:04,320 --> 00:15:05,120
Are you hungry?

264
00:15:06,960 --> 00:15:07,880
I am beginning to.

265
00:15:08,560 --> 00:15:11,600
Is there anything you like?

266
00:15:12,280 --> 00:15:13,120
Anything’s fine.

267
00:15:14,080 --> 00:15:16,480
How about steak?

268
00:15:17,120 --> 00:15:19,480
Isn’t it too heavy for breakfast?

269
00:15:20,040 --> 00:15:20,640
Congee?

270
00:15:21,320 --> 00:15:22,240
Too light.

271
00:15:23,080 --> 00:15:23,720
Noodles!

272
00:15:30,360 --> 00:15:31,160
I’m kidding.

273
00:15:31,920 --> 00:15:32,840
Steak is fine.

274
00:15:34,720 --> 00:15:35,480
Shall we?

275
00:15:37,200 --> 00:15:37,800
Of course.

276
00:15:49,280 --> 00:15:50,520
This is unacceptable!

277
00:15:51,720 --> 00:15:53,920
The ink on the divorce certificate
hasn’t even begun to dry!

278
00:15:57,480 --> 00:16:00,120
Here is the information on all the products.

279
00:16:00,520 --> 00:16:01,080
Right.

280
00:16:05,720 --> 00:16:06,440
Oh, one more thing.

281
00:16:06,560 --> 00:16:11,800
The board of directors issued a new
evaluation system on employees today.

282
00:16:12,440 --> 00:16:14,760
These are the evaluation buttons.

283
00:16:15,440 --> 00:16:16,040
Here.

284
00:16:16,880 --> 00:16:17,560
RATE YOUR SATISFACTION
GOOD/NEUTRAL/AWFUL
OUT OF ORDER
TEMPORARILY OUT OF USE

285
00:16:18,520 --> 00:16:21,720
Your life now depends on these buttons.

286
00:16:24,280 --> 00:16:25,400
Are you serious?

287
00:16:28,400 --> 00:16:29,240
AWFUL

288
00:16:29,240 --> 00:16:31,560
I want it! I want it! I want it!

289
00:16:31,560 --> 00:16:32,520
Don’t push that button, kid…
I want it!

290
00:16:34,000 --> 00:16:34,880
That’s enough.

291
00:16:35,360 --> 00:16:36,280
You can’t have it.

292
00:16:36,280 --> 00:16:37,640
The toys here are expensive,

293
00:16:37,640 --> 00:16:38,760
and you will only ruin it.

294
00:16:38,760 --> 00:16:41,600
But I want it! I want it!

295
00:17:03,760 --> 00:17:05,320
I’ll be fine as long as
there are no house geckos.

296
00:17:30,320 --> 00:17:32,760
Does he know I live here now
and he doesn’t?

297
00:17:34,200 --> 00:17:38,320
Grandpa put him in the kid department.

298
00:17:38,880 --> 00:17:41,880
It was a miracle he could even drag
himself all the way home.

299
00:17:47,520 --> 00:17:48,200
Pai.

300
00:17:48,640 --> 00:17:50,760
Thank you for telling me where you live.

301
00:17:51,680 --> 00:17:53,160
I promise I won’t tell Tim.

302
00:17:54,200 --> 00:17:55,320
Forget about him.

303
00:17:56,040 --> 00:17:57,440
He’s been following me all day.

304
00:17:58,080 --> 00:17:59,680
I bet he knows where I live.

305
00:17:59,960 --> 00:18:01,600
He probably thinks
he was being so smooth, too.

306
00:18:04,880 --> 00:18:06,840
How was the date?

307
00:18:11,800 --> 00:18:12,760
The food was great.

308
00:18:15,000 --> 00:18:15,880
I’ll see you around.

309
00:18:15,880 --> 00:18:17,760
Are you Mr. Pai?

310
00:18:18,320 --> 00:18:18,600
Yes.
You have something in your hair.

311
00:18:23,520 --> 00:18:24,440
You also have something on your face.

312
00:18:26,400 --> 00:18:27,680
You look adorable, you know?

313
00:18:29,120 --> 00:18:30,520
But you’re a bit skinny.

314
00:18:32,240 --> 00:18:33,520
Let’s find something to eat, shall we?

315
00:18:34,400 --> 00:18:35,200
S–Sure.

316
00:18:36,400 --> 00:18:36,960
Mr. Pai.

317
00:18:40,200 --> 00:18:40,840
Watch where you’re going!
I’m sorry.

318
00:18:41,440 --> 00:18:42,560
I told you to watch it!

319
00:18:42,560 --> 00:18:43,560
How dare you!
Hey!

320
00:18:44,320 --> 00:18:45,760
How dare you!

321
00:18:45,760 --> 00:18:47,960
How dare you touch me!

322
00:18:49,160 --> 00:18:50,000
Mr. Pai!

323
00:18:50,960 --> 00:18:51,680
Pai, you jerk!

324
00:18:53,520 --> 00:18:54,400
It’s not working.

325
00:18:55,480 --> 00:18:58,720
I don’t know what to talk about with them.

326
00:19:01,280 --> 00:19:03,040
I don’t feel comfortable around them.

327
00:19:04,840 --> 00:19:07,960
And some of them are
someone I’d never date.

328
00:19:10,440 --> 00:19:12,360
Sounds scary.

329
00:19:15,040 --> 00:19:20,280
If you’re not ready, I think
it’s okay to just take a break.

330
00:19:25,880 --> 00:19:27,040
When Tim was injured,

331
00:19:28,680 --> 00:19:33,320
I was just as scared as when I was
before I knew he was fooling me.

332
00:19:35,640 --> 00:19:36,640
You still love him.

333
00:19:40,320 --> 00:19:40,920
Yes.

334
00:19:42,680 --> 00:19:46,320
And I can’t stop myself from believing him
when he talks about our relationship

335
00:19:47,520 --> 00:19:48,880
as if it was all real.

336
00:19:50,640 --> 00:19:54,000
You still love him and believe in him.

337
00:19:56,160 --> 00:19:57,760
Why are you even looking
for someone new?

338
00:20:01,360 --> 00:20:02,600
I want to start over.

339
00:20:04,360 --> 00:20:06,000
Every time I see Tim’s face,

340
00:20:06,680 --> 00:20:08,920
I can still picture our wedding.

341
00:20:10,800 --> 00:20:14,120
Maybe forgiveness is beyond me.

342
00:20:17,200 --> 00:20:17,760
It…

343
00:20:18,680 --> 00:20:20,800
It would be easier to try
and love someone else.

344
00:20:21,400 --> 00:20:22,240
Don’t you think so, North?

345
00:20:32,480 --> 00:20:33,040
North.

346
00:20:35,400 --> 00:20:35,920
North.

347
00:20:36,680 --> 00:20:37,280
Yes?

348
00:20:38,480 --> 00:20:39,480
Go sleep in bed with U.

349
00:20:43,240 --> 00:20:44,080
Good night.

350
00:20:45,640 --> 00:20:46,800
U.

351
00:21:12,200 --> 00:21:14,640
YOU HAVE A NEW MATCH!
TRY TALKING TO THEM.

352
00:21:14,960 --> 00:21:16,200
ABOUT ME
I AM AN ARCHITECT.

353
00:21:16,200 --> 00:21:19,200
THE ALGORITHM MUST KNOW SOMETHING TO BRING US TOGETHER.

354
00:21:20,000 --> 00:21:23,400
“The algorithm must know something
to bring us together.”

355
00:21:26,480 --> 00:21:28,080
(Is that really how you look?)

356
00:21:28,360 --> 00:21:29,240
(You’re pretty.)

357
00:21:34,240 --> 00:21:37,400
(If you say so.
You don’t show your face in the profile.)

358
00:21:37,760 --> 00:21:40,400
(There are so many ways to know
someone more than just their face, right?)

359
00:21:41,640 --> 00:21:43,640
(I can’t tell who you are from your photo.)

360
00:21:44,400 --> 00:21:45,680
(Then how come you chose
to match with me?)

361
00:21:46,360 --> 00:21:48,560
(I don’t know. I want to trust
the algorithm, I guess.)

362
00:22:26,160 --> 00:22:29,280
Did you think I’d say you don’t look
like your profile picture or something?

363
00:22:31,920 --> 00:22:32,600
Yes.

364
00:22:33,960 --> 00:22:35,600
I didn’t want to be ghosted before
I even got to try to make this work.

365
00:22:43,880 --> 00:22:46,280
What the hell are you doing?

366
00:22:46,800 --> 00:22:47,840
Why are you so deadset on fooling me?

367
00:22:48,600 --> 00:22:50,040
I’m not fooling you, though.

368
00:22:50,400 --> 00:22:52,080
That’s my photo in the profile.

369
00:22:52,080 --> 00:22:54,080
You said you’re an architect!

370
00:22:54,080 --> 00:22:55,600
I am an architect!

371
00:22:55,600 --> 00:22:57,560
I just got my permit.

372
00:22:57,720 --> 00:22:58,680
I’ll show you if you don’t believe me.

373
00:23:00,240 --> 00:23:01,760
I am a certified architect.

374
00:23:02,480 --> 00:23:04,280
And I’ve been practicing on the side, too.

375
00:23:04,520 --> 00:23:06,920
What about the name ‘M’?

376
00:23:07,320 --> 00:23:09,520
M as in Me. That’s me.

377
00:23:10,400 --> 00:23:12,480
What kind of person doesn’t recognize
their own boyfriend?

378
00:23:13,600 --> 00:23:14,440
Hold on.

379
00:23:16,200 --> 00:23:17,880
I didn’t lie to you at all.

380
00:23:18,440 --> 00:23:19,640
I was being myself last night.

381
00:23:20,520 --> 00:23:22,000
More myself than the Tim you knew.

382
00:23:23,280 --> 00:23:24,680
And we got along just fine, didn’t we?

383
00:23:29,720 --> 00:23:30,680
You must be delusional.

384
00:23:31,680 --> 00:23:33,120
I only came today out of politeness.

385
00:23:36,640 --> 00:23:37,760
You’re afraid you’ll forgive me.

386
00:23:39,360 --> 00:23:41,120
Can you stop with that?

387
00:23:42,000 --> 00:23:43,280
I don’t care what you believe to be true.

388
00:23:43,520 --> 00:23:44,320
I’m gone.

389
00:23:46,000 --> 00:23:46,800
My love!

390
00:23:47,240 --> 00:23:48,520
My love, don’t leave me!

391
00:23:48,520 --> 00:23:49,120
My love!
Don’t leave me like this.

392
00:23:50,000 --> 00:23:51,160
Please, my love!

393
00:23:51,440 --> 00:23:52,280
Don’t leave me.

394
00:23:52,360 --> 00:23:53,320
What the hell is wrong with you?

395
00:23:53,320 --> 00:23:56,440
If you abandon me,
how will our baby and I go on?

396
00:23:56,440 --> 00:23:57,240
Baby?

397
00:23:57,560 --> 00:23:58,320
What baby?

398
00:23:58,320 --> 00:23:59,760
My love!

399
00:24:02,600 --> 00:24:07,640
Polyester tent with waterproof coating.

400
00:24:08,760 --> 00:24:10,400
- Fibergla—
- Excuse me.

401
00:24:11,360 --> 00:24:12,800
I need a tent recommendation.

402
00:24:18,120 --> 00:24:22,320
Something even a boy like him can set up on his own.

403
00:24:22,680 --> 00:24:24,720
The easiest way would be to stay home.

404
00:24:25,040 --> 00:24:26,040
Be damned with the tent.

405
00:24:28,720 --> 00:24:29,120
North!

406
00:24:29,680 --> 00:24:30,760
How could you say that to a customer?

407
00:24:32,040 --> 00:24:33,960
Ma’am, I must apologize.

408
00:24:34,240 --> 00:24:36,160
He’s new here so he’s still learning.

409
00:24:36,320 --> 00:24:37,480
“He’s still learning”?

410
00:24:38,000 --> 00:24:40,320
What if he sells me a product that doesn’t work?

411
00:24:41,120 --> 00:24:44,320
The easiest tents to set up are the automatic and the inflatable.

412
00:24:44,800 --> 00:24:45,600
Automatic?

413
00:24:46,120 --> 00:24:48,840
That would take away the heart of camping.

414
00:24:49,440 --> 00:24:50,280
How about…

415
00:24:52,320 --> 00:24:53,760
This one?

416
00:24:54,320 --> 00:24:58,640
It’s compact, dome-shaped, and made of polyester, and it’s waterproof.

417
00:24:58,760 --> 00:24:59,440
The poles—

418
00:24:59,480 --> 00:25:00,880
Can you demonstrate the setup?

419
00:25:12,160 --> 00:25:13,720
What do these buttons do?

420
00:25:15,880 --> 00:25:16,840
Of course!

421
00:25:27,600 --> 00:25:29,480
Go on a date with me.

422
00:25:30,360 --> 00:25:31,160
Come on.

423
00:25:31,640 --> 00:25:32,280
Please!

424
00:25:33,080 --> 00:25:35,320
I will agree if you stop making a ruckus.

425
00:25:36,560 --> 00:25:38,560
So come with me so I can stop.

426
00:25:38,880 --> 00:25:39,800
Where are we going?

427
00:25:44,320 --> 00:25:44,720
Here.

428
00:25:47,760 --> 00:25:48,200
What?

429
00:25:49,560 --> 00:25:51,600
It’s a treasure hunt.

430
00:25:52,200 --> 00:25:54,120
A thrift store like this is where you find rare items, you know?

431
00:25:55,600 --> 00:25:56,760
I don’t want anything here.

432
00:25:57,640 --> 00:25:58,920
They don’t have the kind of clothes I wear.

433
00:26:00,160 --> 00:26:02,120
That’s why I want to take you here.

434
00:26:03,280 --> 00:26:04,840
I want to see what this version of Pai would choose to wear.

435
00:26:05,760 --> 00:26:06,280
“This version of Pai”?

436
00:26:08,440 --> 00:26:10,240
You’re dressed like the CEO of a mall.

437
00:26:10,880 --> 00:26:13,400
But you don’t need to keep up the facade or anything today.

438
00:26:13,880 --> 00:26:15,000
You don’t have to care what your Aunt Kia says.

439
00:26:15,720 --> 00:26:16,920
So you can wear whatever you want.

440
00:26:17,680 --> 00:26:18,320
I’ll pay for it.

441
00:26:19,920 --> 00:26:20,560
You have money?

442
00:26:21,480 --> 00:26:21,800
Of course.

443
00:26:22,600 --> 00:26:23,240
It’s 70 baht per 100 grams, after all.

444
00:26:26,760 --> 00:26:27,160
And you?

445
00:26:27,720 --> 00:26:28,480
Does this outfit reflect who you are?

446
00:26:29,280 --> 00:26:31,080
This is how I’m always dressed.

447
00:26:32,920 --> 00:26:35,320
But I’ll change if you want me to.

448
00:26:38,120 --> 00:26:38,360
Right.

449
00:26:39,120 --> 00:26:39,440
That’s fair.

450
00:26:40,560 --> 00:26:40,720
Let’s go.

451
00:26:47,080 --> 00:26:49,920
I’ll pick the best outfits for you. I’ll make sure you look great.

452
00:26:51,240 --> 00:26:51,840
How about this?

453
00:26:52,560 --> 00:26:52,720
Well?

454
00:26:53,680 --> 00:26:55,520
It suits you.

455
00:26:56,040 --> 00:26:57,200
Makes your skin pop, this one.

456
00:26:58,400 --> 00:26:58,680
Hold on to this.

457
00:27:02,160 --> 00:27:02,480
Hold it.

458
00:27:02,600 --> 00:27:04,000
That’s an option. It’s a good one.

459
00:27:05,000 --> 00:27:05,440
What about this?

460
00:27:06,760 --> 00:27:07,480
Aunt Kia style.

461
00:27:08,640 --> 00:27:08,840
Well?

462
00:27:11,080 --> 00:27:11,680
I’ll add it to the pile.

463
00:27:12,200 --> 00:27:12,440
No.
No?

464
00:27:13,920 --> 00:27:14,120
It’s my personal favorite.

465
00:27:14,440 --> 00:27:15,480
It is.

466
00:27:15,600 --> 00:27:16,560
I know it’s not yours, and that’s okay.

467
00:27:17,120 --> 00:27:17,720
It is mine.

468
00:27:18,920 --> 00:27:20,920
You don’t normally care for T-shirts, though, do you?

469
00:27:21,560 --> 00:27:21,920
Wow.

470
00:27:23,080 --> 00:27:24,360
Now this is a killer.

471
00:27:25,960 --> 00:27:26,720
Rock and roll, you know?

472
00:27:27,760 --> 00:27:28,160
You like this?

473
00:27:30,600 --> 00:27:31,040
You like that?
How about this one?

474
00:27:32,520 --> 00:27:33,000
Here.

475
00:27:33,640 --> 00:27:34,480
You like this.

476
00:27:34,960 --> 00:27:36,160
Now that’s a hit right now.

477
00:27:36,880 --> 00:27:38,000
POLCASAN, you know?

478
00:27:39,280 --> 00:27:40,240
Where has Pai gone?

479
00:27:40,880 --> 00:27:41,840
Camouflage.

480
00:28:15,080 --> 00:28:16,000
I’m Pai of Empire.

481
00:28:16,200 --> 00:28:16,720
You don’t think this is accurate?

482
00:28:17,920 --> 00:28:18,800
Are you making fun of me?

483
00:28:19,400 --> 00:28:19,760
Yes.

484
00:28:21,400 --> 00:28:22,400
Go get changed right now.

485
00:28:30,480 --> 00:28:30,600
Here.

486
00:28:36,560 --> 00:28:37,240
That was tiring,

487
00:28:38,320 --> 00:28:39,600
but it was fun.

488
00:28:42,640 --> 00:28:44,240
Was it as fun as spending time with the other three or four dudes?

489
00:28:46,280 --> 00:28:46,600
No.

490
00:28:47,720 --> 00:28:48,680
You did not even come close to any of them.

491
00:28:49,360 --> 00:28:49,680
Is that right?

492
00:28:50,800 --> 00:28:51,960
How come you haven’t stopped smiling all day, then?

493
00:28:55,440 --> 00:28:55,680
Oh!

494
00:28:56,560 --> 00:28:57,240
The duckling returns!

495
00:28:58,600 --> 00:28:58,800
Ow!

496
00:29:03,720 --> 00:29:06,080
What now?

497
00:29:08,960 --> 00:29:12,960
Well, we’ll grab dinner, and then maybe a drink.

498
00:29:16,400 --> 00:29:20,960
And after that, if there’s still something we want to do, we definitely can.

499
00:29:23,920 --> 00:29:24,480
Keep dreaming.

500
00:29:25,280 --> 00:29:25,600
Hey!

501
00:29:26,720 --> 00:29:30,240
If you get up right now, I’m screaming even louder than before.

502
00:29:31,040 --> 00:29:32,400
I’m shameless, you know?

503
00:29:33,320 --> 00:29:33,880
Try me if you want.

504
00:29:36,120 --> 00:29:37,480
Why are you being so persistent?

505
00:29:42,800 --> 00:29:45,960
You ever met someone so right for you

506
00:29:48,040 --> 00:29:49,600
that no one after could replace him?

507
00:29:52,080 --> 00:29:54,600
You just can’t let him go no matter what.

508
00:30:21,120 --> 00:30:22,720
This is the “easy to set up” option?

509
00:30:23,760 --> 00:30:27,000
Would I need to call a construction crew if this was a hard-to-set-up one?

510
00:30:27,600 --> 00:30:29,680
If you can’t assemble a tent, give it up.

511
00:30:29,760 --> 00:30:31,120
Book a hotel or a homestay instead.

512
00:30:31,320 --> 00:30:34,000
But it was you who said it was easy to set up.

513
00:30:34,160 --> 00:30:36,560
If I said it is difficult, who would buy it?

514
00:30:36,720 --> 00:30:38,640
So you opted to deceive customers by overclaiming?

515
00:30:39,480 --> 00:30:39,800
North.

516
00:30:40,600 --> 00:30:41,880
You can not say that to a customer.

517
00:30:42,200 --> 00:30:43,280
Apologize right now.

518
00:30:43,360 --> 00:30:43,680
But—

519
00:30:43,720 --> 00:30:44,880
No but!

520
00:30:45,240 --> 00:30:46,240
It’s evident you can’t set up the tent.

521
00:30:46,560 --> 00:30:47,560
You’re wasting her time,

522
00:30:47,760 --> 00:30:48,800
and you’re being rude.

523
00:30:50,560 --> 00:30:51,160
Aunt—

524
00:30:52,720 --> 00:30:53,720
This customer—

525
00:30:53,720 --> 00:30:57,920
Ma’am, I must apologize for this mistake.

526
00:30:58,280 --> 00:31:01,760
It is my fault for failing to train my employee well.

527
00:31:02,200 --> 00:31:02,360
Right.

528
00:31:03,960 --> 00:31:08,320
I do hope to receive some good recommendations in the future.

529
00:31:09,800 --> 00:31:13,760
I’ll come by again… to talk to this specific staff member.

530
00:31:16,440 --> 00:31:17,440
Come on, Da Zhan.

531
00:31:19,160 --> 00:31:20,320
Let’s take a look at the toy section.

532
00:31:32,840 --> 00:31:35,320
RATE YOUR SATISFACTION
GOOD/NEUTRAL/AWFUL

533
00:31:39,480 --> 00:31:40,120
Thank you.
Here.

534
00:31:41,960 --> 00:31:42,520
Thank you.

535
00:31:48,000 --> 00:31:49,040
Let’s go, Da Zhan.

536
00:31:55,680 --> 00:31:56,240
What happened?

537
00:31:56,880 --> 00:32:00,160
She just wanted me to recommend some toys for the boy.

538
00:32:00,760 --> 00:32:04,320
So I asked him what kind of skills he’s looking to play the toys with.

539
00:32:05,040 --> 00:32:05,960
And I gave them a demonstration.

540
00:32:06,600 --> 00:32:07,520
They bought everything I showed them.

541
00:32:10,360 --> 00:32:11,480
So she did the same thing.

542
00:32:12,320 --> 00:32:12,480
What?

543
00:32:13,440 --> 00:32:13,760
North?

544
00:32:20,320 --> 00:32:21,920
By the time North becomes mature enough,

545
00:32:22,600 --> 00:32:24,760
no one would care to come to our mall, Papa.

546
00:32:28,560 --> 00:32:29,200
Come in.

547
00:32:34,640 --> 00:32:35,960
What complaint do you have now?

548
00:32:41,040 --> 00:32:41,520
Auntie.

549
00:32:42,320 --> 00:32:46,320
If I could assemble the tent I recommended, you’d buy it, wouldn’t you?

550
00:32:47,160 --> 00:32:48,160
Of course.

551
00:32:49,120 --> 00:32:50,800
I wanted to help you out.

552
00:32:51,320 --> 00:32:52,440
But look how you treated me.

553
00:32:55,800 --> 00:32:56,560
I’m sorry.

554
00:32:59,000 --> 00:33:00,200
I thought you were just trying to mess with me.

555
00:33:01,560 --> 00:33:02,520
Listen to me, North.

556
00:33:03,360 --> 00:33:06,800
The people who come toour mall aren’t here to shop.

557
00:33:06,800 --> 00:33:08,320
They’re here for a walk, for a stroll.

558
00:33:08,720 --> 00:33:10,880
Our job is to entice them into shopping.

559
00:33:12,280 --> 00:33:16,720
Because at the end, it doesn’t matter what they’re doing in your department.

560
00:33:17,040 --> 00:33:19,440
What matters is what you’re doing in your department.

561
00:33:23,840 --> 00:33:24,080
Ugh!

562
00:33:24,800 --> 00:33:27,000
You’re selling tents but you don’t know how to set up a tent.

563
00:33:27,880 --> 00:33:30,920
You’ve been working at the bakery. Did you try all the pastry you’re selling?

564
00:33:32,800 --> 00:33:33,320
No.

565
00:33:34,640 --> 00:33:35,240
Marvelous.

566
00:33:36,440 --> 00:33:38,040
Oh, North.

567
00:33:39,480 --> 00:33:41,840
I advise you to focus on getting through this trainee program.

568
00:33:42,800 --> 00:33:44,120
Otherwise, you wouldn’t survive anywhere.

569
00:33:49,840 --> 00:33:50,800
Y–Yes.

570
00:33:54,840 --> 00:33:58,280
I have to get back to work.

571
00:34:03,560 --> 00:34:04,160
Go on.

572
00:34:10,160 --> 00:34:10,800
Papa.

573
00:34:12,120 --> 00:34:13,600
Don’t baby him.

574
00:34:15,080 --> 00:34:16,360
It’s better he hears all this from me

575
00:34:16,360 --> 00:34:18,800
than for him to go viral on TikTok because he offends some customers.

576
00:34:19,920 --> 00:34:22,320
But North isn’t used to being criticized.

577
00:34:23,280 --> 00:34:25,160
And that’s why he is the way that he is.

578
00:34:41,600 --> 00:34:43,080
It’s the middle of the day.

579
00:34:51,520 --> 00:34:52,520
Why are you screaming?

580
00:34:52,520 --> 00:34:53,600
Where the hell did you come from?

581
00:34:54,120 --> 00:34:55,120
North, you alright?

582
00:34:57,840 --> 00:35:00,000
U…

583
00:35:00,400 --> 00:35:02,040
I’m a loser.

584
00:35:03,080 --> 00:35:04,320
No, that’s not true.

585
00:35:04,400 --> 00:35:05,760
All I do is make mistakes.

586
00:35:11,800 --> 00:35:13,280
I want to comfort you.

587
00:35:14,920 --> 00:35:16,400
But I can’t understand a word you say.

588
00:35:21,760 --> 00:35:22,400
U!

589
00:35:22,680 --> 00:35:23,680
Well, I couldn’t understand.

590
00:35:26,120 --> 00:35:27,440
The most infuriating part was that…

591
00:35:30,400 --> 00:35:31,960
They were right about everything.

592
00:35:34,000 --> 00:35:35,320
When I started this bakery,

593
00:35:36,640 --> 00:35:38,960
I was truly clueless, just like Grandpa said.

594
00:35:40,080 --> 00:35:40,840
I’m just so…

595
00:35:42,840 --> 00:35:43,800
How about this?

596
00:35:45,000 --> 00:35:45,360
Hold on.

597
00:35:52,640 --> 00:35:53,760
Why don’t you try coming up with a recipe?

598
00:35:54,800 --> 00:35:55,800
Maybe make a drink.

599
00:35:56,480 --> 00:35:57,760
Choose what you like.

600
00:35:58,640 --> 00:35:59,920
By the end of the day, you can tell Grandpa

601
00:36:00,280 --> 00:36:01,360
you even came up with a menu item.

602
00:36:18,960 --> 00:36:19,640
Careful.

603
00:36:20,520 --> 00:36:21,320
I’ll add a lemon slice.

604
00:36:29,880 --> 00:36:30,200
Here.

605
00:36:32,120 --> 00:36:34,040
Why did you buy it?

606
00:36:35,280 --> 00:36:38,320
Grandpa won’t soften up just because you made one purchase.

607
00:36:39,920 --> 00:36:40,640
You got it wrong.

608
00:36:41,600 --> 00:36:43,880
I didn’t buy it so you could meet your sales target.

609
00:36:44,720 --> 00:36:47,480
I bought it so you could learn how to assemble it.

610
00:36:53,400 --> 00:36:53,840
What?

611
00:36:55,080 --> 00:36:55,960
How could you come up with that?

612
00:36:56,200 --> 00:36:57,280
That is so thoughtful.

613
00:36:58,200 --> 00:36:58,600
Oww!

614
00:37:02,080 --> 00:37:02,440
Right.

615
00:37:03,280 --> 00:37:03,680
Let’s begin.

616
00:37:04,560 --> 00:37:04,760
Go on.

617
00:37:06,520 --> 00:37:06,880
Alright.

618
00:37:07,400 --> 00:37:08,440
Do you need my help?

619
00:37:08,440 --> 00:37:09,280
No, no, no.

620
00:37:11,960 --> 00:37:15,320
First of all, connect the poles.

621
00:37:15,400 --> 00:37:16,240
Connect the poles.

622
00:37:18,040 --> 00:37:18,960
That doesn't look promising.
Let me help.

623
00:37:19,400 --> 00:37:20,200
No, no, no, no.

624
00:37:21,120 --> 00:37:22,560
I have to learn how to assemble it.

625
00:37:22,680 --> 00:37:23,680
Is this where this goes, U?

626
00:37:24,440 --> 00:37:25,440
Yes.

627
00:37:25,920 --> 00:37:27,480
Now this is getting to the hard part.

628
00:37:27,480 --> 00:37:29,040
You’ll have to help me hold this.

629
00:37:35,160 --> 00:37:35,800
I’ll grab it.

630
00:37:36,840 --> 00:37:38,160
You get that.

631
00:37:38,400 --> 00:37:40,280
There’s no way his grandfather wouldn’t soften up after seeing this.

632
00:37:40,640 --> 00:37:42,920
Oh, my voice must be in the video.

633
00:37:45,560 --> 00:37:48,160
U, I did it!

634
00:37:48,440 --> 00:37:49,320
I assembled a tent!

635
00:37:50,680 --> 00:37:51,040
Good job.

636
00:37:54,160 --> 00:37:55,280
It really is durable.

637
00:37:57,320 --> 00:37:58,200
You’ve never slept in a tent before?

638
00:38:00,200 --> 00:38:03,280
I have, but in the kind of tent that comes with air-conditioning and a bed.

639
00:38:03,880 --> 00:38:06,160
I’ve never slept in the kind that I have to assemble myself before.

640
00:38:09,480 --> 00:38:11,440
You wanna sleep here tonight?

641
00:38:13,960 --> 00:38:16,160
So you can tell customers how it is.

642
00:38:16,760 --> 00:38:18,080
You’ll be an expert on this.

643
00:38:18,560 --> 00:38:18,800
Alright.
Let’s do it.

644
00:38:21,640 --> 00:38:23,280
Hey, you’re going to knock it down.

645
00:38:23,760 --> 00:38:24,400
It’s strong enough.

646
00:38:25,520 --> 00:38:26,240
Don’t knock it down.

647
00:38:27,640 --> 00:38:28,080
Well?

648
00:38:28,760 --> 00:38:29,160
It’s amazing, right?

649
00:38:48,160 --> 00:38:49,800
You’re not even going to take me to a nice bar?

650
00:38:52,320 --> 00:38:53,400
This is my kind of hidden bar.

651
00:38:56,520 --> 00:39:00,160
And this is my special cocktail.

652
00:39:01,480 --> 00:39:02,320
Are you sure it’s edible?

653
00:39:02,720 --> 00:39:03,360
Of course.

654
00:39:04,160 --> 00:39:05,200
It’s full of your favorite things.

655
00:39:20,120 --> 00:39:20,560
It’s good.

656
00:39:21,320 --> 00:39:21,920
See?

657
00:39:22,520 --> 00:39:23,800
I told you it would be good.

658
00:39:26,560 --> 00:39:26,880
Hey.

659
00:39:27,520 --> 00:39:28,400
Slow down.

660
00:39:28,880 --> 00:39:29,440
It’s strong.

661
00:39:32,280 --> 00:39:33,320
But if you want to get drunk, by all means.

662
00:39:34,000 --> 00:39:34,880
I’ll give you a ride home.

663
00:39:35,640 --> 00:39:36,000
No.

664
00:39:36,560 --> 00:39:38,000
I prefer having all my wits about me tonight.

665
00:39:41,600 --> 00:39:42,720
I prefer that, too.

666
00:39:43,280 --> 00:39:45,760
So you can’t blame the alcohol if you decide to fold.

667
00:39:52,760 --> 00:39:54,320
You said this place is special.

668
00:39:55,080 --> 00:39:55,960
There’s nothing special about this.

669
00:40:00,520 --> 00:40:00,680
Come.

670
00:40:13,400 --> 00:40:13,680
Sit down.

671
00:40:22,800 --> 00:40:23,200
Look up.

672
00:41:06,640 --> 00:41:07,840
What is all this, U?

673
00:41:09,200 --> 00:41:09,560
North.

674
00:41:13,920 --> 00:41:14,200
Come here.

675
00:41:16,480 --> 00:41:17,640
What?

676
00:41:18,600 --> 00:41:19,000
Sit down.

677
00:41:25,160 --> 00:41:25,440
Oh!

678
00:41:27,440 --> 00:41:27,720
You see that, North?

679
00:41:28,560 --> 00:41:29,040
Over there.

680
00:41:32,160 --> 00:41:32,640
What?

681
00:41:33,840 --> 00:41:34,200
Here.

682
00:41:37,160 --> 00:41:37,520
Look.

683
00:41:39,360 --> 00:41:39,760
Where?
There.

684
00:41:40,760 --> 00:41:41,160
There?

685
00:41:45,760 --> 00:41:47,240
A tiger?

686
00:41:48,640 --> 00:41:50,000
We could be eaten.

687
00:41:50,400 --> 00:41:51,240
A tiger?

688
00:41:51,360 --> 00:41:53,080
Oh, my!

689
00:41:53,640 --> 00:41:54,720
We’re going to be eaten.

690
00:41:55,320 --> 00:41:55,760
I’m so scared.

691
00:42:00,760 --> 00:42:01,920
You’re unbelievable.

692
00:42:04,080 --> 00:42:06,200
I can’t take you to South Africa.

693
00:42:06,360 --> 00:42:08,720
So I’m bringing South Africa to you.

694
00:42:11,120 --> 00:42:12,560
You sure this is just as good?

695
00:42:13,280 --> 00:42:13,960
Of course.

696
00:42:16,400 --> 00:42:16,960
Well…

697
00:42:19,720 --> 00:42:20,280
What else is there?

698
00:42:23,320 --> 00:42:23,800
Of course, there is.

699
00:42:24,320 --> 00:42:25,640
Oh, that’s bad…

700
00:42:27,040 --> 00:42:27,360
Look.

701
00:42:28,960 --> 00:42:30,000
A herd of zebras.

702
00:42:32,760 --> 00:42:34,000
On the neighborhood’s shrine.

703
00:42:35,520 --> 00:42:36,360
Oh, U!

704
00:43:04,680 --> 00:43:05,280
What are you laughing at?

705
00:43:07,520 --> 00:43:08,400
Did you drop your car key?

706
00:43:10,800 --> 00:43:13,600
Why did you tell me to take you here?

707
00:43:19,800 --> 00:43:23,840
I just want to know if I meet this version of you here,

708
00:43:25,240 --> 00:43:25,880
would I like you.

709
00:43:41,120 --> 00:43:42,280
Why did everything have to be a lie?

710
00:44:02,920 --> 00:44:03,520
I’m sorry.

711
00:44:09,280 --> 00:44:12,320
It’s been a very good date today.

712
00:44:13,800 --> 00:44:16,800
But I don’t know if it’s because I like who you are,

713
00:44:18,440 --> 00:44:19,720
or if it’s because I’m still in love with you.

714
00:44:23,520 --> 00:44:24,440
I want to fall in love with someone else.

715
00:44:26,840 --> 00:44:28,160
Anyone who resembles you even just a little.

716
00:44:29,600 --> 00:44:30,320
But there’s no one.

717
00:44:33,480 --> 00:44:34,120
Resembles me?

718
00:44:36,320 --> 00:44:37,000
Do you mean…

719
00:44:38,680 --> 00:44:39,720
the me that I am now or the one you fell for?

720
00:44:51,760 --> 00:44:52,960
My life used to be full of mess,

721
00:44:56,720 --> 00:44:58,360
but now I have no one.

722
00:45:02,520 --> 00:45:03,640
Even Grandpa chose only North.

723
00:45:05,720 --> 00:45:08,880
I should be furious that you’re being so hard to get rid of,

724
00:45:10,480 --> 00:45:13,920
but all I feel is relieved that I still see you every time I turn around.

725
00:45:18,200 --> 00:45:19,000
I told you

726
00:45:21,080 --> 00:45:22,280
I’m not letting you go.

727
00:45:47,240 --> 00:45:49,280
How could our relationship work, Tim?

728
00:45:50,080 --> 00:45:51,480
How could I forget everything that happened?

729
00:45:52,920 --> 00:45:53,480
You don’t have to forget.

730
00:45:55,960 --> 00:45:59,720
If you have to be mad at me for the rest of our lives, I’ll be here.

731
00:46:47,680 --> 00:46:49,000
I told you not to cry.

732
00:46:50,200 --> 00:46:50,760
You look like a duckling.

733
00:46:51,320 --> 00:46:52,160
Duckling, my foot.

734
00:46:53,240 --> 00:46:53,960
I’m serious.

735
00:46:55,840 --> 00:46:56,520
What are you doing here?
The mall is closed!

736
00:46:57,840 --> 00:46:58,200
Run!
Wait.

737
00:46:59,480 --> 00:46:59,840
Where are we going?

738
00:46:59,840 --> 00:47:01,000
You don’t own this place anymore, you know?

739
00:47:01,320 --> 00:47:01,880
Run!

740
00:47:19,400 --> 00:47:21,000
I have to be at the client’s office.

741
00:47:21,440 --> 00:47:23,440
So I’ll be busy.

742
00:47:24,360 --> 00:47:27,600
Someone misses him like crazy, huh?

743
00:47:27,760 --> 00:47:28,960
I don’t miss him!

744
00:47:29,120 --> 00:47:31,280
Someone in the same department broke up last week.

745
00:47:31,560 --> 00:47:32,520
I don’t want to break up!
What?

746
00:47:33,800 --> 00:47:36,320
I’m sorry for making you feel bad.

747
00:47:38,200 --> 00:47:38,880
I made this for you.

748
00:47:40,440 --> 00:47:41,680
The weather is perfect.

749
00:47:43,680 --> 00:47:45,360
We just need a blackout and we’re all set.

